## Step 2
The uniform distribution on $(0,1)$ has a mean $\mu = \frac{0+1}{2} = 0.5$ and variance $\sigma^2 = \frac{(1-0)^2}{12} = \frac{1}{12}$. Therefore, the standard deviation $\sigma = \sqrt{\frac{1}{12}}$.

## Step 3
The mean of the sample, $\bar{X}$, has a mean $\mu_{\bar{X}} = \mu = 0.5$ and a standard deviation $\sigma_{\bar{X}} = \frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}} = \frac{\sqrt{\frac{1}{12}}}{\sqrt{12}} = \sqrt{\frac{1}{12} \times \frac{1}{12}} = \frac{1}{12}$.

## Step 4
To apply the CLT, we standardize $\bar{X}$ to $Z = \frac{\bar{X} - \mu_{\bar{X}}}{\sigma_{\bar{X}}} = \frac{\bar{X} - 0.5}{\frac{1}{12}} = 12(\bar{X} - 0.5)$.

## Step 5
Now, we can calculate $P(1/2 \leq \bar{X} \leq 2/3)$ by converting the limits to $Z$ scores. For $\bar{X} = 1/2$, $Z = 12(1/2 - 0.5) = 0$. For $\bar{X} = 2/3$, $Z = 12(2/3 - 0.5) = 12 \times (2/3 - 1/2) = 12 \times (4/6 - 3/6) = 12 \times (1/6) = 2$.

## Step 6
Using a standard normal distribution table, $P(0 \leq Z \leq 2) = P(Z \leq 2) - P(Z \leq 0) = 0.9772 - 0.5 = 0.4772$.

